A longer index than the annular is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men with a longer index than the annular are at lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger is a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men before 60," said co-author Ros Eeles, professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could help determine which men should undergo prostate cancer testing, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health outbreaks, said Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain over 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right hand index shorter than the annular.
For them as for 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
For those with the longer index than the annular, however, the risk fell to 33 per cent, for men before 60 years of age the risk decrease reached 87 per cent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it was precisely testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech genetician and former president of the Academy of Science, said to CTK that he is aware of this study but that he does not, it seems to him, that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer is "fully demonstrated."
