The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, widens the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say that it shows that life has opportunities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organization has a double capacity."
"It can develop either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"This is why it is very special, even though it is far from being a truly" foreign "life form," said Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in the online edition of Thursday's Science journal.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But researchers have discovered that the bacterium, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to develop after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"We are wondering what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
Discovery is important in life research beyond the Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the finding, generated widespread speculations on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of an alien life.
This has not been the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other planetary environments, organizations could be able to use other elements to activate biochemistry and that the" standard "set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, could not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, Professor at the Institute of Planetary and Spacial Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure," said Cockell.
It wasn't a fortuitous discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Astrology Institute, who led the study, chose Lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so it speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances could be able to replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behaviour is really similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, organizations have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately."
"But arsenic is quite different enough to not work exactly like phosphorus; it enters inside and, in a way, gums the work of our biochemical machine," Anbar explained.
Researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a life form using arsenic may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, Assistant Professor of Microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing has ever shown that it could work.
The arsenic was more common at the beginning of the Earth's existence, she said; for example, the researchers hypothesized that the first life forms could have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways to form life, not just the way life on Earth was formed at first, "said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
