The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
People must go to Visa Claimant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the United States Embassy and Consulate will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to report to Visa Claimant Service Centres (CSA, according to its acronyms in English) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be revised by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some benefits for aspirants, including:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for application visas (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for trader and investor visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visas will not be required to present themselves at an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves to the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Because of the fact that biometric information will be taken from the CSA, applicants who wish to have a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in it less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service rate of $26.
For more information on the new visa procedure, visit http: / / mexico.usembassy.gov / boletines / sp101201 _ Visas-FAQs.html
