A global plan to renovate lighting
The United Nations proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to achieving a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved in order to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in line with the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to have adopted in Cancún to compensate for the absence of binding commitments to reduce by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if incandescent light bulbs that still monopolize 50-70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent light bulbs or, better, by light light light light bulbs (LED or "LED" in English), most of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of global fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that should increase global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to detract from this balance sheet again 5 Gt in order to stabilize the 2-degree-centigrade rise in climate by 2020 in order to avoid it becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, this energy need is reduced by two more times.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new light bulbs at DEL, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company has also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent light bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all new bulbs can also work with rheostats as well as emit very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
A number of specialists have shown reservations to fluocompact bulbs since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers set up instructions.
However, the report notes, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not compact fluorescent bulb, but rather coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States only, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion per year in electricity purchases and $8 million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 billion thermal power plants, the construction of which would cost it $2.5 billion.
