Climate: how France bids its pledges for funding
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the implementation of the fast start or early funding promises made by developed countries.
And the big French bidouillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (€420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU released the great game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation is appreciable and valued at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had reached EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to meet its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, be "new and additional," in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference year: international financing is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years under fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 to be "new and additional."
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditures or to the overall level of official development assistance.
Concretely, France's total support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each chooses its method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1 €lended is equivalent to 1 €given.
Of course, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are cost-effective (often projects related to mitigation of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as an equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan for the lender country (equivalent to an interest rate).
But France only has such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of €420 million by making 91.5% of loans (€389.8 million) and 8.5% of grants (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in other words) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the very large majority of the European Union puts €1 to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
Nice pass-by tower!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand, on the evolution of the action over time and on the other, on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, it can make it believe that it spends €420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has made the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since developing countries are not completely dupe...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relative short-term issue in relation to all climate discussions.
But it could be another grain of sand in the huge machine that UNFCCC is.
Let us hope that will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting mode for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of compliance with its commitments and equity with other EU countries.
But above all, France could move forward on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans will not be overlooked.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
