These standard meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liter of water per day - and friandises, have been reviewed by laboratories in search of chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens, and five substances classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that may act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Centre for Cancer Research.
"Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each individual chemical taken are not exceeded, we see in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and / or PE is of concern," notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than ten possible carcinogens and three proven carcinogens, as well as about 20 residues that may disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as an incas by the study, presents traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide that is still prohibited in France.
Same for Kenya's green beans, included in lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide prohibited in the EU.
In addition, haché steak, canned tuna, and even bread wand and chewing gum were truffled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, salmon steak was the "wealthiest" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the meal to the microwave was not free.
The final risk to the consumer of this "contaminant cocktails" is probably underestimated, "according to the study.
The Europe Ecologie-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization."
In July, a study by the European Food Security Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
